WEBVTT

00:00:36.102 --> 00:00:41.602
<v Ahmed Kabir Chaion> Hello everyone. Welcome once again
to WordPress Accessibility Day 2020.

00:00:41.627 --> 00:00:45.805
This is a 24 hour long event
where we talk about accessibility.

00:00:46.849 --> 00:00:48.831
My name is Ahmed Kabir Chaion

00:00:48.856 --> 00:00:51.765
and I'm working as a
Business Development Manager at weDevs.

00:00:51.790 --> 00:00:55.104
I'm also a regular contributor
to the making WordPress documentation,

00:00:55.129 --> 00:00:57.694
design, polyglots, accessibility,

00:00:57.718 --> 00:01:00.469
hosting community, learn WordPress,
and Marketing team.

00:01:00.494 --> 00:01:02.925
I will be your host for this session.

00:01:02.949 --> 00:01:07.468
You're here for the 10 am UTC talk
with Calum Ryan.

00:01:07.493 --> 00:01:10.943
Please feel free to add your question
to the YouTube chat feed

00:01:10.967 --> 00:01:12.721
and we'll answer those at the end.

00:01:13.550 --> 00:01:16.803
So how do we approach accessibility,

00:01:16.828 --> 00:01:21.530
while testing in a way that's sufficiently
comprehensive from a technical perspective,

00:01:22.554 --> 00:01:28.608
at the same time presentable to clients
without being technically knowledgeable and

00:01:28.633 --> 00:01:30.458
who may themselves have a disability.

00:01:30.760 --> 00:01:34.090
So that's a question posed
specifically for this talk.

00:01:34.399 --> 00:01:35.793
So in this talk,

00:01:35.817 --> 00:01:40.075
the speaker will explain some
of the approaches and attention to detail

00:01:40.100 --> 00:01:45.491
it takes to test and present accessibility
issues in websites that's accessible.

00:01:46.023 --> 00:01:48.241
The points that will be covered:

00:01:48.265 --> 00:01:52.398
using WordPress to help make accessible,
accessibility reports for clients,

00:01:52.700 --> 00:01:56.899
the conversations with clients
as part of the accessibility testing process

00:01:56.924 --> 00:01:58.111
before and after,

00:01:58.123 --> 00:02:01.567
and what the benefits are
of using this approach.

00:02:02.020 --> 00:02:06.564
Our speaker Calum is an
Accessibility Consultant for dxw,

00:02:06.589 --> 00:02:10.207
helping the public sector
make their websites more accessible.

00:02:10.232 --> 00:02:15.421
His background is in frontend
web development and user interface design,

00:02:15.833 --> 00:02:18.957
having worked in the web industry
for around 10 years,

00:02:18.981 --> 00:02:21.828
which brings to this session accessible—

00:02:24.948 --> 00:02:26.463
which brings to this session

00:02:27.173 --> 00:02:29.139
making accessibility—

00:02:29.173 --> 00:02:31.979
making accessible accessibility reports.

00:02:32.003 --> 00:02:34.242
Apologies for that. Calum, take it away.

00:02:38.184 --> 00:02:39.269
<v Calum Ryan> Thank you.

00:02:39.294 --> 00:02:45.325
So I was really pleased to give this talk
about creating accessibility reports,

00:02:45.350 --> 00:02:47.338
which are accessible.

00:02:47.362 --> 00:02:52.119
And I work for a
company called dxw

00:02:52.746 --> 00:02:56.665
who are based in the UK,
in London and Leeds

00:02:57.691 --> 00:02:59.635
has around 70 people roughly.

00:03:00.382 --> 00:03:04.960
And we design, build, operate,
improve digital public services.

00:03:10.028 --> 00:03:18.008
And within dxw, I work in GovPress
which specifically works with WordPress.

00:03:18.539 --> 00:03:21.900
We have lots of clients who use WordPress.

00:03:21.924 --> 00:03:24.149
They're all public sector mainly.

00:03:24.835 --> 00:03:27.028
And throughout the past two months,

00:03:27.028 --> 00:03:31.199
I've been working on making
the websites more accessible

00:03:31.734 --> 00:03:36.203
and this is for the latest legislation

00:03:36.801 --> 00:03:39.352
which is now a legal requirement in the UK

00:03:39.376 --> 00:03:42.951
for all public sector websites
to be accessible.

00:03:44.221 --> 00:03:48.137
If you take a look at
accessibility.campaign.gov.uk

00:03:48.764 --> 00:03:52.300
there's more explanation
on what that involves,

00:03:52.324 --> 00:03:55.050
the regulations and who that applies to.

00:03:56.468 --> 00:04:04.431
So within organization of GovPress,
I'm the only accessibility expert

00:04:04.456 --> 00:04:09.638
and it's been my responsibility
to interpret a lot of that information

00:04:09.662 --> 00:04:13.835
from the WCAG guidelines,

00:04:13.860 --> 00:04:19.901
the latest guidelines which all
public sector organizations must comply to.

00:04:21.591 --> 00:04:25.174
So if some of you, I mean it depends…

00:04:26.214 --> 00:04:29.362
I'm sure there's a whole range of people
listening to this talk,

00:04:29.814 --> 00:04:32.628
but if you're more technically minded,

00:04:32.652 --> 00:04:35.061
you might have already seen 
these guidelines.

00:04:35.086 --> 00:04:39.219
They are an extensive documentation

00:04:39.251 --> 00:04:41.647
and listing of all the
different requirements

00:04:41.671 --> 00:04:43.404
for having an accessible website.

00:04:44.714 --> 00:04:50.467
I've probably spent some, quite a few hours
bedtime reading for this.

00:04:50.492 --> 00:04:53.706
It's not the sort of thing
you can just read off in an hour.

00:04:53.730 --> 00:04:56.382
It's certainly something
you need to get your head around

00:04:56.898 --> 00:05:00.072
when you're looking at how
accessible websites should be.

00:05:01.882 --> 00:05:04.904
In those guidelines I can summarize that

00:05:04.929 --> 00:05:10.050
websites need to be perceivable,
operable, understandable and robust.

00:05:12.337 --> 00:05:15.505
So that's a lot of criteria
to present to clients

00:05:16.070 --> 00:05:21.423
and what I'm looking at,
in terms of report,

00:05:22.605 --> 00:05:28.167
is for clients to understand the
importance of having accessible websites

00:05:29.159 --> 00:05:32.753
and for that reports being useful to them,

00:05:33.518 --> 00:05:38.473
that not only before, but after the report,
they can see which fixes have been done

00:05:38.497 --> 00:05:42.077
and which fixes are the most critical
that need to be done

00:05:42.442 --> 00:05:46.585
and which are less important, but
still need to be looked at at some point.

00:05:49.660 --> 00:05:54.363
In terms of the report going forward
as well, it's a useful tool

00:05:54.396 --> 00:05:56.852
for the clients that we have

00:05:56.876 --> 00:05:59.470
to create their own accessibility statement

00:05:59.495 --> 00:06:00.843
which is a requirement

00:06:01.610 --> 00:06:04.381
for this guidelines at the moment,

00:06:04.406 --> 00:06:06.116
for certainly in the UK

00:06:06.141 --> 00:06:09.501
for the legislation that even if
your website is fully accessible

00:06:09.525 --> 00:06:11.520
you still have an accessibility statement.

00:06:15.290 --> 00:06:18.850
So in terms of actually
creating an accessibility report,

00:06:20.234 --> 00:06:25.238
there's a methodology
which you can look at from w3.org

00:06:25.715 --> 00:06:32.823
which gives a good in-depth listing of
all the different criteria to look through

00:06:32.848 --> 00:06:36.074
and how to actually
structure your accessibility report.

00:06:36.863 --> 00:06:41.947
Now this is alone something
we wouldn't present to our clients

00:06:41.972 --> 00:06:46.142
because it is a very detailed

00:06:46.845 --> 00:06:50.245
and quite technical presentation

00:06:50.270 --> 00:06:54.202
on highlighting what has been tested

00:06:54.226 --> 00:06:55.575
and who has tested it

00:06:55.599 --> 00:06:57.615
and the types of tests
that have been performed.

00:06:58.107 --> 00:07:02.373
So the challenge that
I wanted to get around

00:07:03.091 --> 00:07:08.159
was looking at what accessibility
reports do at the moment

00:07:08.754 --> 00:07:11.076
and how we can make that more accessible

00:07:11.100 --> 00:07:15.566
to not only the people who are going to be
fixing the technical issues in the website,

00:07:15.591 --> 00:07:17.151
but the content issues,

00:07:17.726 --> 00:07:20.980
the overall readability of the content.

00:07:22.027 --> 00:07:27.284
So typically we'll have a lot of
different people looking at the report.

00:07:27.308 --> 00:07:32.423
So it's important that we make
that report as accessible as possible

00:07:32.448 --> 00:07:34.956
to everybody who is not only reading it,

00:07:34.981 --> 00:07:39.837
but actually putting in information
and issues into that report.

00:07:41.115 --> 00:07:45.627
Typically there'll be many issues which are
the same over different pages on websites

00:07:46.155 --> 00:07:49.470
and the similar solutions
as well to fix those issues.

00:07:51.875 --> 00:07:56.776
And also in terms of our own example

00:07:56.800 --> 00:07:58.754
where we have many different clients,

00:07:59.286 --> 00:08:03.211
we need to have multiple people
editing those reports

00:08:03.235 --> 00:08:04.552
or reviewing those reports.

00:08:04.577 --> 00:08:10.774
So we needed a solution to allow
different people to look at those reports

00:08:10.799 --> 00:08:11.925
at the same time.

00:08:13.435 --> 00:08:15.550
We also had quite a short deadline

00:08:15.582 --> 00:08:19.245
to create all of these
reports for different clients

00:08:19.270 --> 00:08:25.237
so having a facility to make those reports
in the most efficient and accurate way

00:08:25.262 --> 00:08:26.290
was very important

00:08:27.079 --> 00:08:32.039
and having a way to present
very technical language

00:08:32.531 --> 00:08:36.366
in a way which doesn't
completely take over the report

00:08:36.755 --> 00:08:40.656
and make it difficult for somebody
who isn't technically minded

00:08:40.680 --> 00:08:44.359
to get to the most
important points in the report.

00:08:46.426 --> 00:08:53.335
And also a lot of our clients are
just used to having a PDF to print off

00:08:53.746 --> 00:08:55.409
whenever they look at documents.

00:08:55.442 --> 00:09:00.780
So, although PDFs aren't inherently
that accessible, we still have that option

00:09:00.805 --> 00:09:03.630
for the report to be printed off as a PDF

00:09:04.182 --> 00:09:06.050
or just as a paper printout.

00:09:10.466 --> 00:09:13.156
So creating accessibility report.

00:09:13.762 --> 00:09:17.777
We decided to use WordPress because
WordPress is what we use day-to-day

00:09:17.802 --> 00:09:19.367
in our company.

00:09:19.391 --> 00:09:25.584
We have a whole team of people
who can not only work on the backend,

00:09:25.609 --> 00:09:28.367
but develop a front-end user interface,

00:09:28.784 --> 00:09:30.465
can customize themes,

00:09:30.490 --> 00:09:34.572
and WordPress just generally
has got a great community of people

00:09:34.596 --> 00:09:39.834
to make the whole content
management system a lot more robust.

00:09:41.445 --> 00:09:46.342
It's important to say we don't
actually use Gutenberg in our reports.

00:09:46.367 --> 00:09:49.066
We still use the Classic editor interface,

00:09:49.853 --> 00:09:51.805
and that goes back to my—

00:09:52.194 --> 00:09:57.131
my intention is to make this report
not only accessible for the front end,

00:09:57.156 --> 00:10:01.389
but accessible for people
who are creating reports,

00:10:01.414 --> 00:10:05.702
so the whole way of entering
information into reports

00:10:05.726 --> 00:10:10.978
is using the standard WordPress
content management system,

00:10:11.003 --> 00:10:13.993
without any of the Gutenberg changes.

00:10:17.659 --> 00:10:21.375
So starting with how we create the reports,

00:10:21.399 --> 00:10:26.187
we use, if anybody is
familiar with WordPress,

00:10:26.212 --> 00:10:29.790
on the backend
we use a number of existing plugins,

00:10:29.814 --> 00:10:32.127
where we use the Classic Editor

00:10:32.944 --> 00:10:36.968
the override, so we don't get the
Gutenberg presentation.

00:10:36.993 --> 00:10:39.189
We use Custom Fields—

00:10:39.659 --> 00:10:42.577
Advanced Custom Fields—
which gives us a few more options

00:10:43.323 --> 00:10:48.907
in terms of adding extra fields to content

00:10:49.376 --> 00:10:53.869
and making that more easy
to add repeated content.

00:10:53.894 --> 00:10:58.344
So if you've got like a
repeated issue or repeated criteria,

00:10:58.369 --> 00:11:02.240
we can just start typing the words
for that criteria

00:11:02.265 --> 00:11:04.113
and it will populate field

00:11:04.138 --> 00:11:08.177
without us having to go through and repeat
the same thing for every single report.

00:11:10.831 --> 00:11:18.181
We use Custom Post Types to
store the solutions and the criteria

00:11:18.721 --> 00:11:22.463
as a centralized area of content

00:11:22.487 --> 00:11:25.727
so we can refer back
to those pieces of content

00:11:25.752 --> 00:11:27.755
and put those into each report,

00:11:27.779 --> 00:11:31.870
and that helps make the whole
process a lot more efficient and accurate.

00:11:33.348 --> 00:11:37.749
And in terms of presenting
the reports to clients,

00:11:37.774 --> 00:11:42.460
we use the standard password protection
on posts when we publish them,

00:11:42.484 --> 00:11:47.700
so that only the client with a
password can review that report.

00:11:51.843 --> 00:11:55.416
In terms of actually
viewing the reports as a user,

00:11:56.356 --> 00:12:02.812
we try and comply to
WCAG 2.1 (AA) standard.

00:12:03.525 --> 00:12:07.494
So everything we do is
client compliant to that level.

00:12:08.327 --> 00:12:12.774
You can navigate the entire report
using keyboard, screen reader,

00:12:12.799 --> 00:12:19.468
and each of the sections are all
accessible through a single navigation.

00:12:20.181 --> 00:12:23.804
And supposing I was to say that
the whole report is a single page.

00:12:24.252 --> 00:12:27.037
So if you want to print it off you can,

00:12:27.070 --> 00:12:30.311
just print off as a PDF if you wish.

00:12:31.256 --> 00:12:36.533
And in terms of beyond
the technical standards,

00:12:36.558 --> 00:12:39.192
we also look at how readable language is.

00:12:39.217 --> 00:12:44.498
So, if we've got a
technical term such as ARIA,

00:12:44.522 --> 00:12:46.026
A-R-I-A,

00:12:46.050 --> 00:12:49.299
we explain what that abbreviation means

00:12:50.481 --> 00:12:54.951
and in terms of the whole
sort of general design system,

00:12:54.976 --> 00:13:00.408
we try to apply standards
which are accessible.

00:13:00.432 --> 00:13:06.016
So we have gov.uk has their own design
system and we take influence from that.

00:13:06.041 --> 00:13:11.921
So things such as the issues which
I'll show you in a short while

00:13:13.175 --> 00:13:18.758
in reports are all using standard
components, which are accessibility tested.

00:13:23.139 --> 00:13:25.526
So let's look inside
the accessibility report.

00:13:28.518 --> 00:13:33.541
Initially the report was a prototype
which I developed without WordPress.

00:13:34.168 --> 00:13:37.569
So this report is flexible,

00:13:37.593 --> 00:13:39.509
we can use what—

00:13:40.970 --> 00:13:44.268
anybody could use the report
in whatever CMS

00:13:44.293 --> 00:13:47.569
or even just a static template
if they wanted to.

00:13:49.751 --> 00:13:54.481
The current set we have
is a WordPress setup

00:13:54.506 --> 00:13:59.610
that is fairly customizable
to however you need it to be.

00:14:02.785 --> 00:14:05.488
So we start off with saying
who created the report,

00:14:06.570 --> 00:14:08.109
outlining the person.

00:14:08.133 --> 00:14:10.303
That was optional if they
want to have their avatar

00:14:10.867 --> 00:14:14.493
or any other information
about when the report was done,

00:14:15.263 --> 00:14:17.085
what their role is in the organization

00:14:17.747 --> 00:14:22.437
and outlining if there was anybody else
who quality checked the report

00:14:23.655 --> 00:14:26.764
and the overall compliance of report.

00:14:26.788 --> 00:14:30.978
So in some cases we
have clients who stipulate

00:14:31.002 --> 00:14:34.671
they want their website
to be up to AAA standard,

00:14:34.696 --> 00:14:37.227
so we'll make a differentiation

00:14:37.251 --> 00:14:42.044
between websites which have
been checked to AA or AAA.

00:14:48.063 --> 00:14:52.097
So in terms of outlining what we tested,

00:14:52.121 --> 00:14:57.879
we created a list of say how many pages
or PDFs have been tested

00:14:58.498 --> 00:15:01.784
and then outlining how it's being tested,

00:15:01.808 --> 00:15:07.534
so we always specify the automated
and manual tests which we've done.

00:15:07.977 --> 00:15:11.883
We have different browsers
and different devices we use

00:15:11.908 --> 00:15:13.849
and different combinations we use.

00:15:14.421 --> 00:15:17.603
Typically that will involve
a few screen readers.

00:15:18.024 --> 00:15:19.563
We have a limited team.

00:15:20.500 --> 00:15:23.955
You can actually do that
so although we have—

00:15:23.979 --> 00:15:26.331
there are several
different screen readers—

00:15:26.356 --> 00:15:28.907
we only test with what we have available.

00:15:29.389 --> 00:15:34.179
At the moment, we test with
VoiceOver, NVDA,

00:15:34.204 --> 00:15:37.723
and the mobile equivalent.

00:15:37.748 --> 00:15:40.287
So we've got VoiceOver on iOS

00:15:40.311 --> 00:15:43.056
and TalkBack on Android

00:15:44.024 --> 00:15:46.080
and Narrator on Windows.

00:15:47.358 --> 00:15:51.555
And we'll probably look at having some more
when we maybe expand actually a bit more

00:15:52.130 --> 00:15:53.790
in the accessibility side of things.

00:15:53.814 --> 00:15:58.259
So this is giving an outline
of just how it's being tested

00:15:58.791 --> 00:16:04.513
and that is before any of the issues
or outlining how we fix those issues.

00:16:08.624 --> 00:16:16.241
Now the issues identified in report,
we typically have four user impact levels.

00:16:16.266 --> 00:16:22.045
So that starts with minor,
moderate, serious and critical.

00:16:23.859 --> 00:16:32.132
These are user impact levels
we take from the Axe tool by Deque

00:16:32.423 --> 00:16:35.103
and we use that as platform automated tests

00:16:35.127 --> 00:16:39.352
to get an overview of what are
the main issues with websites

00:16:39.733 --> 00:16:41.543
before moving on to the manual tests.

00:16:41.568 --> 00:16:48.669
And so within our report we can
use things such as the accordions

00:16:48.694 --> 00:16:51.640
from the gov uk design system

00:16:51.665 --> 00:16:58.415
to make the whole collection
of issues more simplified

00:16:58.439 --> 00:17:00.305
and more collated.

00:17:00.330 --> 00:17:02.132
So if there's an issue,

00:17:02.157 --> 00:17:04.557
if it's the same issue on different pages,

00:17:04.581 --> 00:17:07.338
it's a lot easier to just
go to that single issue

00:17:07.767 --> 00:17:10.878
and outline it within a certain section.

00:17:10.903 --> 00:17:17.450
So for each user impact level
we have these accordion items

00:17:17.697 --> 00:17:24.025
which as a description of the image
that we have to the right of the slide

00:17:24.050 --> 00:17:29.572
is the critical issue's title,
with the issue,

00:17:30.705 --> 00:17:33.445
the type of test, so in this
case it's an automated test

00:17:34.866 --> 00:17:36.429
and where the issue is located.

00:17:36.453 --> 00:17:40.568
So in this case,
we have the home page navigation

00:17:40.593 --> 00:17:44.657
and then after that we say
the level that it has been assessed to.

00:17:44.681 --> 00:17:50.376
So in this case
the level has been WCAG 2.0, AA

00:17:52.019 --> 00:17:57.434
and the specific criteria that
the issue is not complying with,

00:17:57.458 --> 00:18:00.897
is 1.4.3 contrast minimum.

00:18:02.582 --> 00:18:08.601
So following those details we outline
what is the problem and who it affects.

00:18:09.299 --> 00:18:14.057
So in this case we have
multiple instances of contrast

00:18:14.081 --> 00:18:15.988
between foreground and background colors.

00:18:16.013 --> 00:18:18.721
It doesn't meet the
contrast ratio threshold

00:18:19.410 --> 00:18:22.359
and this includes
banners, post dates,

00:18:22.750 --> 00:18:27.243
this has a serious user impact because
there are many types of vision impairments

00:18:27.268 --> 00:18:31.035
where poor color contrast could
affect their ability to view the website.

00:18:34.468 --> 00:18:39.191
Then after that we have
screenshots of where that is present.

00:18:40.032 --> 00:18:44.881
Now this also helps for again
people who aren't technically minded

00:18:44.906 --> 00:18:48.045
to actually get an idea
of where the problem is.

00:18:49.389 --> 00:18:52.001
So in this case we have
four small screenshots

00:18:52.607 --> 00:18:56.098
which can be opened
in a light box kind of presentation,

00:18:56.123 --> 00:18:57.485
if you want to expand it,

00:18:59.028 --> 00:19:03.107
and within that we may
also have code samples.

00:19:03.738 --> 00:19:06.853
In this example we don't have
that, but in some we would do.

00:19:09.568 --> 00:19:12.851
And finally in the issue
is the recommended solution.

00:19:14.129 --> 00:19:17.205
We decided to put the solutions
in a separate section.

00:19:18.010 --> 00:19:21.983
So in this case we have a small
summary of what the solution is

00:19:22.515 --> 00:19:25.889
and an anchor link
to the solution further down.

00:19:31.824 --> 00:19:37.662
So the solutions section is again a
collated list of what the solutions are.

00:19:37.687 --> 00:19:42.287
Typically a solution may be
applicable to different issues

00:19:42.311 --> 00:19:46.623
and in this case we have an
image again on the right slide

00:19:46.648 --> 00:19:50.200
with a few issues of being given solutions.

00:19:50.684 --> 00:19:54.732
And in this case we have one about ARIA,

00:19:55.122 --> 00:19:56.312
removing ARIA,

00:19:57.364 --> 00:20:01.740
one about changing HTML here
because the bottom element isn't used,

00:20:03.164 --> 00:20:07.657
and another one for changing the color
contrast because of background color.

00:20:08.554 --> 00:20:13.075
So within each of these solutions
we give the outline of the solution,

00:20:13.099 --> 00:20:14.331
how to fix it.

00:20:14.355 --> 00:20:18.837
In some cases the solution
is aimed at a technical person.

00:20:18.862 --> 00:20:22.642
In some cases the solution
is aimed as a content person.

00:20:22.667 --> 00:20:25.671
So in this example,
we don't actually specify that,

00:20:25.695 --> 00:20:30.095
but in a future iteration of this
whole platform we're going to do

00:20:30.579 --> 00:20:36.576
make a lot clearer on who that
issue, who that solution is aimed at

00:20:36.601 --> 00:20:38.299
in terms of responsibility.

00:20:40.393 --> 00:20:43.409
And finally we refer again to the criteria

00:20:44.103 --> 00:20:46.200
that the solution is applicable to

00:20:46.915 --> 00:20:51.885
and again that is another anchor link
to a section further down in the report.

00:20:57.163 --> 00:21:00.280
And finally in the report we
have the references section.

00:21:00.915 --> 00:21:08.852
This again links you to the
WCAG reference for the criteria.

00:21:09.427 --> 00:21:12.035
In each case we also have a secondary link

00:21:12.059 --> 00:21:19.760
to an explanation of how to
understand that criteria a bit more.

00:21:20.148 --> 00:21:25.308
In both cases the explanation has a
lot more than we can write and report.

00:21:26.014 --> 00:21:29.880
And one of the reasons
why I decided not to include

00:21:29.904 --> 00:21:33.702
an entire description of the criteria
in the report itself,

00:21:34.234 --> 00:21:37.542
again it's just not to make
it so overwhelming for different people

00:21:37.567 --> 00:21:38.644
in the report

00:21:38.913 --> 00:21:42.961
and to make the report a reasonable level
for everybody using it.

00:21:48.881 --> 00:21:52.015
So what have we learned
from creating this platform?

00:21:53.507 --> 00:21:57.687
Certainly early on we've found there's
a lot of information to include in a report

00:21:57.712 --> 00:22:03.076
and using visual space effectively is
certainly something which you need to

00:22:03.101 --> 00:22:06.725
when you've got so much
information to interpret

00:22:06.749 --> 00:22:10.497
to a vast range of different people
you might be viewing the report.

00:22:12.100 --> 00:22:13.902
We often have different clients

00:22:14.485 --> 00:22:19.328
and this is an example,
we have the Office for National Statistics

00:22:19.923 --> 00:22:22.960
and in such an example as that,

00:22:22.984 --> 00:22:28.244
we may be creating reports to a more
customized level than maybe some others

00:22:28.688 --> 00:22:30.685
in terms of the people viewing it,

00:22:30.717 --> 00:22:33.935
in terms of what they
need from the reports.

00:22:34.324 --> 00:22:37.211
There are ways that we
might consider making it

00:22:37.235 --> 00:22:39.828
more customizable
than it is at the moment.

00:22:42.443 --> 00:22:47.274
In terms of, again, going back to
who the issues are applicable to,

00:22:47.306 --> 00:22:50.461
who's responsible for fixing those issues,

00:22:51.170 --> 00:22:54.020
we should maybe look at
making that bit more clearer.

00:22:55.801 --> 00:22:58.107
In the discussions we've had with clients,

00:22:58.131 --> 00:23:03.909
I've found that often many will
feel that the report is really just for

00:23:03.934 --> 00:23:05.803
a technical person to look at

00:23:06.196 --> 00:23:10.661
and really they're just
there just to view reports

00:23:10.686 --> 00:23:14.206
and summarize that the timing,

00:23:14.230 --> 00:23:18.831
actually understand how much time
they need for the fixes to be made.

00:23:18.856 --> 00:23:23.983
Whereas in many cases the fixes are
for their own team of content editors

00:23:24.514 --> 00:23:29.311
and decision makers to spend time
making lots of fixes themselves

00:23:32.454 --> 00:23:38.380
And then also finally looking at
the report in terms of how crucial it is

00:23:38.405 --> 00:23:40.523
to making websites more accessible,

00:23:41.277 --> 00:23:48.109
it's only a complement to discussion
and ongoing discussion with clients

00:23:48.134 --> 00:23:51.089
to understand about how to
make the websites more accessible

00:23:51.624 --> 00:23:58.447
and going forward that the report
is only a one-off snapshot in time.

00:23:58.472 --> 00:24:01.727
That they need to understand that
making their website accessible

00:24:01.752 --> 00:24:03.061
is an ongoing process

00:24:03.091 --> 00:24:06.088
which they need to revisit frequently

00:24:06.113 --> 00:24:09.867
and not just as a one-off
to meet this legislation.

00:24:14.806 --> 00:24:17.255
So what's next for our report platform?

00:24:18.491 --> 00:24:22.113
We currently have the platform
in our own private repository.

00:24:22.541 --> 00:24:26.668
It's not really in a state where
we could open source it right now.

00:24:26.702 --> 00:24:31.613
But we would like to make it open source
as potentially a WordPress plugin

00:24:31.638 --> 00:24:38.005
and also just as a static template that
you can work as your own presentation

00:24:38.030 --> 00:24:40.442
for any content management system.

00:24:42.274 --> 00:24:46.056
It would also be great to get users
to test out the platform,

00:24:46.543 --> 00:24:48.623
not only as content editors,

00:24:48.648 --> 00:24:51.016
but as users viewing the report

00:24:51.040 --> 00:24:55.083
and we'd like to do some
usability testing with people

00:24:55.108 --> 00:25:01.263
to really understand what are the problems
are in interpreting that information

00:25:01.288 --> 00:25:04.632
and how to make reports more accessible.

00:25:06.525 --> 00:25:11.364
And then finally also to make the
whole process a lot more streamlined

00:25:11.389 --> 00:25:16.948
we'd like to link those issues
into a tracking integration.

00:25:16.972 --> 00:25:20.918
So for example, if you're
using a system such as GitHub

00:25:21.703 --> 00:25:26.240
or Trello potentially
having a link with it in that,

00:25:26.264 --> 00:25:29.677
so potentially maybe
it's something like an API

00:25:29.702 --> 00:25:33.515
so that we could make
that whole information a lot more open

00:25:33.539 --> 00:25:40.477
and easier to link to
certain aspects of the report.

00:25:41.341 --> 00:25:43.487
And not only developers,

00:25:43.519 --> 00:25:48.662
but anybody else who wants to see
the progress of changes being fixed

00:25:48.687 --> 00:25:53.871
and any other information basically
is a lot more easily accessible.

00:25:56.331 --> 00:26:01.282
So really I'm probably
finishing quite early for this, but

00:26:02.559 --> 00:26:04.470
just as a roundup really
I just wanted to say

00:26:04.494 --> 00:26:08.520
thank you to everybody
who's organized this event.

00:26:08.545 --> 00:26:13.283
And I am happy to take
questions now or later.

00:26:13.680 --> 00:26:20.269
The company dxw.com, do a whole range
of work in the public sector.

00:26:20.294 --> 00:26:25.778
And if you are based in London,
Leeds, or anywhere within the UK,

00:26:26.151 --> 00:26:29.479
we're happy to talk about
how we can work for you

00:26:29.504 --> 00:26:32.686
in making not only the
web more accessible

00:26:32.711 --> 00:26:37.136
but helping public sector
services and service design.

00:26:38.518 --> 00:26:39.565
Thank you.

00:26:43.604 --> 00:26:45.228
<v Ahmed> Thank you so much, Calum.

00:26:45.930 --> 00:26:49.426
I believe we have a lot of
time for questions.

00:26:50.339 --> 00:26:55.356
We can, but we certainly are not seeing
that much questions in the chat.

00:26:55.943 --> 00:26:58.158
So I would like to ask you
a personal question.

00:26:59.197 --> 00:27:01.324
What would you like to see in the future?

00:27:01.349 --> 00:27:04.017
You mentioned about
open source as a plugin,

00:27:04.042 --> 00:27:06.471
would you give us a bit
more details about that?

00:27:09.118 --> 00:27:13.294
A little bit more in-depth idea about
how the future, accessible future to you.

00:27:15.279 --> 00:27:17.191
<v Calum> Sure.

00:27:17.238 --> 00:27:21.694
So my background is in mainly,
sort of front end user interface design

00:27:22.209 --> 00:27:27.347
and I think making the
whole developer process

00:27:27.389 --> 00:27:33.331
a lot more friendly in terms of
the linking of issues to a system

00:27:33.356 --> 00:27:37.812
which makes things like
continuous integration,

00:27:37.836 --> 00:27:43.368
so developing a way for accessibility
testing in an automated way

00:27:43.393 --> 00:27:46.999
a lot more easy to
include in the build process.

00:27:47.024 --> 00:27:52.682
And if that can be, I think
mainly in my report context,

00:27:52.707 --> 00:27:56.844
but generally the availability
of accessibility testing

00:27:56.869 --> 00:28:00.042
in continuous integration and development

00:28:00.067 --> 00:28:05.812
make that process look more
well documented and promoted.

00:28:06.193 --> 00:28:07.630
That would be great.

00:28:07.907 --> 00:28:09.505
Making the web more accessible

00:28:09.530 --> 00:28:14.787
I think is something which a lot of the
developers I've spoken to

00:28:15.680 --> 00:28:17.098
aren't really aware of enough

00:28:17.122 --> 00:28:20.668
and how to make that process
maybe more easier, I think.

00:28:22.333 --> 00:28:23.348
<v Ahmed> Thank you.

00:28:23.373 --> 00:28:25.514
So my next question to you is:

00:28:25.539 --> 00:28:30.823
based on your experience, where do
you think accessibility is successful more?

00:28:30.848 --> 00:28:34.669
Is it total— is it more
leaning towards technology

00:28:34.694 --> 00:28:37.463
or to acceptance of the use of technology?

00:28:40.245 --> 00:28:42.242
<v Calum> Sorry, if you
could repeat that again, sorry.

00:28:42.267 --> 00:28:46.056
<v Ahmed>Sure. So where do you
think the success lies for accessibility,

00:28:46.080 --> 00:28:47.273
overall accessibility?

00:28:47.334 --> 00:28:50.692
Is it on the use of more technology

00:28:50.717 --> 00:28:55.412
or making it aware for people to
be able to use those technologies?

00:28:55.437 --> 00:28:57.540
Is it on awareness or on technology?

00:28:57.565 --> 00:29:01.798
How would you prioritize it,
the success of accessibility?

00:29:02.750 --> 00:29:04.460
<v Calum> I think certainly both.

00:29:04.493 --> 00:29:07.045
Though, there's room for
improvement on the latter point,

00:29:07.069 --> 00:29:10.309
I think certainly more
in terms of awareness

00:29:10.334 --> 00:29:14.440
and making it more attractive,

00:29:14.465 --> 00:29:22.430
taking away some of the barriers to how
we present that accessibility information.

00:29:22.455 --> 00:29:26.208
How we make it easier
for developer relations to,

00:29:26.946 --> 00:29:29.498
not only just see it as an afterthought,

00:29:29.522 --> 00:29:31.420
but something you start doing

00:29:32.365 --> 00:29:35.864
as soon as you start
writing one line of code,

00:29:35.889 --> 00:29:39.170
you know how you're going to test it

00:29:39.194 --> 00:29:44.553
and where there might be
potential problems for different users.

00:29:46.355 --> 00:29:49.036
<v Ahmed> Right. So another question.

00:29:49.061 --> 00:29:50.970
These are all coming from me,

00:29:50.995 --> 00:29:53.370
so I really appreciate this opportunity

00:29:53.394 --> 00:29:57.064
for me to get firsthand
experience of asking the question.

00:29:57.089 --> 00:30:01.909
So I want to know, while trying
to explain accessibility to people

00:30:01.933 --> 00:30:06.055
who is not totally aware of
such a thing which exists,

00:30:06.080 --> 00:30:09.316
would you share some of
your experience of struggling

00:30:09.341 --> 00:30:15.028
and trying to find it very difficult
to make someone understand

00:30:15.053 --> 00:30:16.852
the importance of having accessibility.

00:30:19.748 --> 00:30:23.907
<v Calum> Sure. I think the
perceptions of accessibility

00:30:23.932 --> 00:30:25.568
certainly on the web

00:30:25.592 --> 00:30:30.786
are very limited from my
experience of speaking to developers

00:30:30.811 --> 00:30:35.646
and being able to convince them

00:30:35.670 --> 00:30:39.862
that what they're doing is important

00:30:39.887 --> 00:30:46.186
and that I think it's something
where they're certainly improving.

00:30:46.211 --> 00:30:50.435
And certainly events like this
are helping with that process,

00:30:50.935 --> 00:30:53.174
but just a general awareness

00:30:53.198 --> 00:30:58.544
is again something which I see lacking
in my experience of speaking to people

00:30:59.060 --> 00:31:03.742
and if there's a way of making
that process just a little bit easier

00:31:04.408 --> 00:31:08.978
in terms of the testing
process and auditing websites

00:31:09.003 --> 00:31:14.102
to understand that, is certainly
some way to go I think.

00:31:14.127 --> 00:31:18.704
And there are tools
which are making that progress easier

00:31:18.729 --> 00:31:22.062
and the browser tools
which I mentioned, Axe,

00:31:22.602 --> 00:31:25.181
and Lighthouse to some extent as well.

00:31:25.665 --> 00:31:30.398
They are tools which I've found
have opened up some awareness more

00:31:30.423 --> 00:31:32.144
in terms of accessibility.

00:31:33.712 --> 00:31:35.490
I'll still say that there's some way to go.

00:31:36.966 --> 00:31:38.169
<v Ahmed> All right, thank you so much.

00:31:38.194 --> 00:31:40.556
We did get a question from the chat.

00:31:40.581 --> 00:31:45.389
So the question is, how can we
follow process for the code liberation

00:31:45.414 --> 00:31:47.580
from your accessibility report plugin?

00:31:48.167 --> 00:31:49.778
And there's a form of comment,

00:31:49.802 --> 00:31:56.228
I'm sure that WordPress a11y community
could help to translate and contribute.

00:31:56.577 --> 00:31:59.675
And also the person
says, thanks for the talk, Calum.

00:32:01.683 --> 00:32:05.283
<v Calum> So thank you.
So yeah the report tool is

00:32:06.096 --> 00:32:09.681
something which it is
intentioned to make it open source.

00:32:10.308 --> 00:32:16.706
The code is all pretty much just
WordPress based templates

00:32:16.731 --> 00:32:21.136
and WordPress based plugins.

00:32:21.161 --> 00:32:23.924
So things like custom fields

00:32:23.948 --> 00:32:28.150
and the presentation itself
is relatively easy just to share

00:32:28.443 --> 00:32:32.748
and I'd like to do that
within the next couple of months hopefully.

00:32:33.637 --> 00:32:35.720
We are open about doing it

00:32:36.351 --> 00:32:40.610
and not just as an internal tool, but
something to help other organizations with.

00:32:40.635 --> 00:32:44.600
So certainly,
we'll try and put up on GitHub

00:32:44.624 --> 00:32:46.350
for the next few months if we can.

00:32:47.845 --> 00:32:50.335
<v Ahmed> Absolutely!
So thank you so much Calum

00:32:50.359 --> 00:32:54.410
for taking the time and
initiative for speaking today

00:32:54.435 --> 00:32:55.986
at this event—

00:32:56.327 --> 00:33:00.052
24 hour long talking about
accessibility, being part of it.

00:33:00.716 --> 00:33:04.221
What other initiatives would
you encourage to stakeholders,

00:33:05.102 --> 00:33:08.109
if they could make a change,
they could make a difference,

00:33:08.134 --> 00:33:10.189
who would you encourage to step forward

00:33:10.213 --> 00:33:13.848
so that accessibility can become
more easily available

00:33:13.873 --> 00:33:16.874
for everyone to understand,
accept and apply?

00:33:19.028 --> 00:33:22.056
<v Calum> So do you mean
in terms of the organizations?

00:33:22.081 --> 00:33:25.832
<v Ahmed> Yeah, the big ones,
policy makers, government.

00:33:28.967 --> 00:33:32.655
<v Calum> Yeah I think certainly credit
to some of the people in the government

00:33:32.680 --> 00:33:34.524
who are stepping forward.

00:33:36.004 --> 00:33:38.367
Maybe not so much the current government,

00:33:38.392 --> 00:33:45.801
but in terms of the people working
on terms as the gov.uk guidelines

00:33:45.825 --> 00:33:52.437
and the overall drive to make at least
the government's website more accessible,

00:33:52.462 --> 00:33:55.502
that's certainly setting a good standard.

00:33:56.441 --> 00:33:58.698
I think in terms of private sector as well,

00:33:58.722 --> 00:34:03.815
there's some great
examples of organizations

00:34:05.440 --> 00:34:10.491
I'm trying to think of one
now, but potentially Monzo

00:34:10.515 --> 00:34:14.920
who are one of the organizations
in creating online banking

00:34:16.110 --> 00:34:20.268
if they were possibly more vocal
on what they're doing for accessibility

00:34:20.293 --> 00:34:22.129
that's a good example there,

00:34:22.923 --> 00:34:27.298
but also some of the more
established private sector organizations

00:34:27.323 --> 00:34:29.506
and the banking sector certainly

00:34:30.006 --> 00:34:37.769
because so many banks are essential to
making our day-to-day lives um possible

00:34:37.794 --> 00:34:38.965
through accessible websites.

00:34:38.989 --> 00:34:42.274
So that's certainly somewhere
which would be great to see.

00:34:42.299 --> 00:34:47.389
I know Barclays in the UK do a great effort

00:34:47.413 --> 00:34:51.357
towards not only accessibility
on their own website,

00:34:51.382 --> 00:34:53.119
but talking about it, being more open.

00:34:53.144 --> 00:34:56.861
So that's certainly one I'd reference.

00:34:58.212 --> 00:34:59.307
<v Ahmed> Alright, Calum.

00:34:59.531 --> 00:35:02.694
with that we wrap up
the Q&amp;A session as well.

00:35:02.718 --> 00:35:08.002
Thank you so so much once again
for your support towards the initiative

00:35:08.027 --> 00:35:12.923
and we hope to see you again in future
WordPress Accessibility Day celebrations

00:35:12.948 --> 00:35:13.985
such as this one.

00:35:14.010 --> 00:35:17.056
I would also like to thank everyone
for attending the session

00:35:17.080 --> 00:35:19.024
with Calum Ryan and myself.

00:35:19.049 --> 00:35:26.998
You can continue the conversation using
the #wpad, #wpad2020 and @wpaccessibility.

00:35:27.665 --> 00:35:31.171
Also don't forget to attend the
next talk: "Digital Transformation

00:35:31.196 --> 00:35:34.827
or Social Digital Transformation
